ervice in Mesopotamia were char-</div><div class="t m18f x31 h9 y5e8 ff3 fs5 fc0 sc0 ls0 ws0">acterized by jealousy, contention, and intrigue. One sister sought to outdo </div><div class="t m44d x31 h9 ya0a ff3 fs5 fc0 sc0 ls0 ws0">the other in the number of sons she bore as both vied for first place in their </div><div class="t m137 x31 h9 ya0b ff3 fs5 fc0 sc0 ls0 ws0">husband&apos;s affections. Son-in-law and father-in-law shone in their game of </div><div class="t m18b x31 h9 ya0c ff3 fs5 fc0 sc0 ls0 ws0">one-upmanship with Laban manifesting interest only in his own advance-</div><div class="t m12f x31 h9 ya0d ff3 fs5 fc0 sc0 ls0 ws0">ment. The biblical story notes more faith in potions and human schemes </div><div class="t m564 x31 h9 y93f ff3 fs5 fc0 sc0 ls0 ws0">than in God. Yet, these same chapters also reveal how groundless is trust in </div><div class="t m3f9 x31 h9 y941 ff3 fs5 fc0 sc0 ls0 ws0">human power and how certain is the reality of the divine promises of mercy, </div><div class="t m508 x31 h9 ye9 ff3 fs5 fc0 sc0 ls0 ws0">forgiveness, and acceptance. At the Jabbok repentant Jacob became Israel, </div><div class="t m448 x31 h9 y943 ff3 fs5 fc0 sc0 ls0 ws0">and God&apos;s plan triumphed in spite of the apparently unpromising human </div><div class="t m47a x31 h9 ya0e ff3 fs5 fc0 sc0 ls0 ws0">material with which He had to work. </div><div class="t m106 x73 ha y87d ff5 fs5 fc0 sc0 ls0 ws0">DAY I. JACOB&apos;S FAMILY (Gen. 29:31-30:43). </div><div class="t m742 x1c hf y2b6 ff5 fs6 fc0 sc0 ls0 ws0">r</div><div class="t m743 x1e hf y2b6 ff5 fs6 fc0 sc0 ls0 ws0">a </div><div class="t m744 x42 hf y2b6 ff5 fs6 fc0 sc0 ls0 ws0"> </div><div class="t m3d2 xc ha y880 ff5 fs5 fc0 sc0 ls0 ws0">1. Jacob&apos;s Children (Gen. 29:31-30:24). </div><div class="t m745 xc h9 ya0f ff3 fs5 fc0 sc0 ls0 ws0">Jacob&apos;s marriage to two sisters, which later Mosaic law prohibited </div><div class="t m40c x3a ha ya10 ff5 fs5 fc0 sc0 ls0 ws0">76 </div><div class="t m746 x3a h45 